		<description><![CDATA[<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="0" width="400" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font><b>Geothermal Intro</b>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<a href="#Overview;balloonFlyto">U.S. Data</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<a href="#AboutData;balloonFlyto">About the Data</a></font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2">&amp;nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font size="+3"><b>Enhanced Geothermal Systems (EGS)</b></font><br /><br /><font size="+3">U.S. Geothermal Resource</font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="left"><hr /><object width="380" height="300"><param name="movie" value="http://www.youtube.com/v/O6r_3AgI49Y&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1&amp;rel=0"></param><param name="allowFullScreen" value="true"></param><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/v/O6r_3AgI49Y&amp;hl=en&amp;fs=1&amp;rel=0" type="application/x-shockwave-flash" allowfullscreen="true" width="380" height="300"></embed></object><p><font size="+1">Enhanced Geothermal Systems (EGS) expand the potential of geothermal energy by orders of magnitude.</font></p><p><font size="+1">Conventional geothermal systems, known as hydrothermal, tap into naturally occurring reservoirs of hot water and steam below the surface of the earth. EGS, by comparison, replicates these natural reservoirs by fracturing hot rock, circulating water through the system, and using the resulting steam to power a turbine, generating electricity. The water is then re-injected back into the rock, continuing the cycle in a closed loop. Since EGS' main requirement is heat, reservoirs could be built modularly where rock is hot enough to produce power [typically &amp;gt;150&amp;deg;C (302&amp;deg;F)]. EGS and hydrothermal are baseload, generating power 24 hours a day, 365 days a year.</font></p><p><font size="+1">Approximately 10,715 MW of hydrothermal generation capacity is currently installed around the world in regions such as Italy, California, and Indonesia. It is one of the lowest cost renewable technologies and provides energy for tens of millions of people. Hydrothermal resources are also commonly used for residential, municipal, and industrial heating.</font></p><p><font size="+1">For more information on Geothermal and EGS:<ul><li><a href="http://iga.igg.cnr.it/index.php">International Geothermal Association</a></li><li><a href="http://www.geothermal.org/">Geothermal Resources Council</a></li><li><a href="http://www.geo-energy.org/">Geothermal Energy Associaion</a></li><li><a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/geothermal/">U.S. Department of Energy Geothermal Technologies Program</a></li></ul></font></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="bottom"><font size="+2"><a href="http://www.google.org/egs">www.google.org/egs</a></font></td><td align="right" valign="bottom"><a href="http://www.google.org"><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/dotorg-logo.png" width="100" height="25" /></a></td></tr></table>]]></description>

			<description><![CDATA[<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="0" width="400" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font><a href="#Geothermal;balloonFlyto">Geothermal Intro</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<b>U.S. Data</b>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<a href="#AboutData;balloonFlyto">About the Data</a></font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2">&amp;nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font size="+3"><b>Continental U.S.</b></font><br /><font size="+2">Geothermal Resource (3-10 km Depth)</font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><hr /><img src="http://chart.apis.google.com/chart?cht=bhs&amp;chs=380x190&amp;chd=t:15,86,158,176,194,235,237%7C0,5,34,99,148,146,153%7C0,0,1,13,47,103,132%7C0,0,0,0,5,18,57%7C-1,-1,-1,-1,0,1,8&amp;chds=0,600,0,600,0,600,0,600,0,600&amp;chco=FFF633,FFCC33,FF9900,FF0000,990066&amp;chtt=Generation+Potential+by+Depth+%26+Temperature%7C(2%25+Recovery)&amp;chdl=150+deg+C%7C200+deg+C%7C250+deg+C%7C300+deg+C%7C350+deg+C&amp;chxt=y,x,x&amp;chxl=0:%7C9.5+km%7C8.5+km%7C7.5+km%7C6.5km%7C5.5+km%7C4.5+km%7C3.5+km%7C1:%7C0%7C150,000%7C300,000%7C450,000%7C600,000%7C2:%7C+%7CMegawatts%7C+&amp;chbh=15,2" /><br /></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="1" padding="0" width="400" bgcolor="#EEEEEE"><tr><td align="left" valign="middle" width="60%"><font size="+1">Total Generation Capacity 2006<br />&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;(All Sources: Coal, Gas, etc.):</font></td><td align="right" valign="middle" width="40%"><font size="+2"><b> 981,800 &amp;nbsp; MW &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</b></font></td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="middle" width="60%"><font size="+1">Enhanced Geothermal Potential<br />&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;(2% Recovery):</font></td><td align="right" valign="middle" width="40%"><font size="+2"><b> 2,072,100 &amp;nbsp; MW &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</b></font></td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="middle" width="60%"><font size="+1">Enhanced Geothermal Potential<br />&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;(20% Recovery):</font></td><td align="right" valign="middle" width="40%"><font size="+2"><b> 20,721,005 &amp;nbsp; MW &amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;</b></font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="left"><br /><p><font size="+1">Enhanced Geothermal Systems (<a href="#Geothermal;balloonFlyto">EGS</a>) harness the essentially unlimited heat of the earth to generate baseload renewable electricity. In this Google Earth layer, you can explore the geothermal resource distribution and electric generation potential of the continental United States, between depths of 3-10 km (9,842-32,808 ft.).<br /><br />This layer was developed in conjunction with the <a href="http://smu.edu/geothermal/">SMU Geothermal Laboratory</a>. <br /><br />More information <a href="#AboutData;balloonFlyto">about this layer</a> and <a href="#Geothermal;balloonFlyto">about EGS</a>.</font></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="left"><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" padding="0" width="400" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><tr><td><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/PlacesScreenshot-sm.png" height="208" width="146" /></td><td align="left"><font size="+2"><b>Explore the layer</b> using the <b>Places panel</b></font><br /><br /><font size="+1">Click <b>Overview</b> to read about the content.<br /><br />Select the <b>3-D</b> folder to see EGS potential mapped by state.<br /><br />Select overlays to see temperature at <b>other depths</b>.</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="bottom"><font size="+2"><a href="http://www.google.org/egs">www.google.org/egs</a></font></td><td align="right" valign="bottom"><a href="http://www.google.org"><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/dotorg-logo.png" width="100" height="25" /></a></td></tr></table>]]></description>

		<Folder id="AboutData">
			<name>About the Data</name>
			<snippet></snippet>
			<description><![CDATA[<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" padding="0" width="400" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font><a href="#Geothermal;balloonFlyto">Geothermal Intro</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<a href="#Overview;balloonFlyto">U.S. Data</a>&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;#124;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;<b>About the Data</b></font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2">&amp;nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="center"><font size="+3"><b>About the Data</b></font><br /><font size="+2">U.S. Geothermal Resource</font></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" align="left"><p><hr /><br /><font size="+2"><b>About the Maps</b><br /> (Temperature at Depth Maps):</font><br /><font size="+1">These maps depict measured and estimated temperatures at depth in 1 km (3,280 ft.) intervals derived from thousands of thermal data points. Temperature contour colors depict gradients of 25 &amp;deg;C (77 &amp;deg;F). The maps and resource estimates were produced by the <a href="http://smu.edu/geothermal/">SMU Geothermal Laboratory</a> as part of their project to update the <a href="http://smu.edu/geothermal/2004NAMap/2004NAmap.htm">Geothermal Map of North America</a>.</font><br /><a href="http://smu.edu/geothermal/"><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/LogoSMUGeothermalLabRB.png"/></a><hr /><br /><font size="+2"><b>About the Generation Potential Estimates</b><br /> (Resources by State):</font><br /><font size="+1">The generation potential estimates represent installed capacity in megawatts electric assuming 30-year operating life, net-cycle efficiencies of available technology, and 2% thermal recovery factor. Recovery factor refers to the percent of total thermal energy underground (3-10 km) recoverable through wells. The United States Geological Survey uses a recovery factor of 10% for their estimates of EGS resources. Also included, are estimates using an optimistic, but plausible, recovery factor of 20% - which dramatically increases generating potential. Geothermal systems can sustain power production for decades and recharge their heat naturally over time. But for the purpose of these estimates, project life is constrained to 30 years.<br /><br />These estimates are based on the "resource base" estimates, power conversion methodologies, and assumptions in <a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/geothermal/pdfs/egs_chapter_2.pdf">Chapter 2</a> and <a href="http://www1.eere.energy.gov/geothermal/pdfs/egs_chapter_3.pdf">Chapter 3</a> of the 2006 <a href="http://web.mit.edu">MIT</a> report, "<a href="http://geothermal.id.doe.gov/publications/future_of_geothermal_energy.pdf">The Future of Geothermal Energy</a>," and as updated by <a href="http://smu.edu/geothermal">SMU</a>. <br /><a href="http://web.mit.edu"><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/mit-logo-full.png" /></a><br /><br />The Total Generation Capacity statistics are from the U.S. Energy Information Administration's <a href="http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/electricity/epa/epa_sum.html">Electric Power Annual</a> 2006 report, published in November, 2007 (<a href="http://www.eia.doe.gov/cneaf/electricity/epa/epa.pdf">download PDF</a>). The figures represent Net Summer Capacity by state for all generation sources, excluding Alaska and Hawaii.<br /><br />The 3-D view shows each state extruded vertically, representing EGS potential as volume, and resource density as height. To see the 3-D view, select it in the Places Panel to the left of the map window.</font><hr /><br /><font size="+2"><b>Visualization</b></font><br /><font size="+1">This Google Earth layer was produced by the Renewable Energy Cheaper Than Coal Initiative (RE&amp;#60;C) at <a href="http://www.google.org">Google.org</a>.</font><br /></p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr><tr><td align="left" valign="bottom"><font size="+2"><a href="http://www.google.org/egs">www.google.org/egs</a></font></td><td align="right" valign="bottom"><a href="http://www.google.org"><img src="http://sites.google.com/site/dotorgearth/files/re-c/dotorg-logo.png" width="100" height="25" /></a></td></tr></table>]]></description>
